ation (c. 1636–c. 1661). It argues that these writers translated Virgil in order to display and interrogate their political loyalties, articulate personal responses to past traumas and express their hopes for the country’s future. All of Virgil’s English translators in this period were in some way associated with the royalist cause, but the political elements of their respective translations demonstrate that royalism itself was not a monolithic political standpoint and instead encompassed a wide variety of opinions regarding the policy of individual monarchs and the institution of monarchy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPolitics in literaturexHistoryy17th century. 0aRoyalistszGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aCalvert, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillespie, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021 Englishz978311075405608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021z9783110753813oZDB-23-DGD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311078040640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147447566240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474475662423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474475662/original  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075405-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-078040-6  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_E